Meet faculty, staff, students and alumni as well as learn about the university?s graduate school admissions process and best practices for passing the Graduate Record Examination (GRE). Application fees will be waived for attendees who apply within a week of the open house.  Tarleton-Fort Worth offers master?s programs in accounting, business administration, clinical mental health counseling, communication studies, counseling, criminal justice, curriculum and instruction, educational administration, medical laboratory services, nursing administration, nursing education, public administration and social work.  The university?s doctor of education (Ed.D.) program combines individualized study with specialized course work and research.

The College of Graduate Studies wants to help you start 2018 in the best way possible, so join us for our New Year, New You Extravaganza on Saturday, January 20.  This event is exclusively offered for graduate and undergraduate students from any campus enrolled at Tarleton for the Spring 2018 semester.  Tarleton December 2017 graduates are also welcome to attend.  Come for as much or as little of the event as your schedule allows?  Event activities will include:  Free on-site document shredding Free professional headshot photos by photographer Matthew Lahey Free GRE Strategy Session presented by The Princeton Review Free professional development workshops   This will be a wonderful opportunity to refresh and renew for the new year.  All students who attend the event will be entered into a drawing to win a guaranteed $500 scholarship for the Spring 2018 semester!  And students who attend the event and submit an admissions application to the College of Graduate Studies within a week of the event will have their $45.00-application fee waived.  Happy New Year!

The Department of Psychological Sciences is hosting Mr. Max Glauben, a Holocaust survivor. This experience is a once in a lifetime chance to hear a first-hand account of a Holocaust survivor?s story. Mr. Glauben is from Warsaw, Poland. His family?s apartment overlooked a square that saw early fighting in the Warsaw Ghetto uprising. He lost all of his family, except for his father, with whom Max was sent to forced labor camps. His father did not survive, and Max came to the U.S. in 1947 as an orphan. This is an opportunity that you will not want to miss, and the event is limited to the first 300 people.   All proceeds from this event will be used to directly support students with limited financial resources who will study abroad with the Holocaust in Europe program in May of 2018. Contact Dr. Jamie Borchardt at 254-968-1970 or borchardt@tarleton.edu if you have any questions.

Are you attending tomorrow?s New Year, New You Extravaganza?  If so, guess what?  The number of $500 scholarship prizes has now increased from 3 to 5!    In addition to the three winners who will be chosen by live drawing once the Extravaganza ends at 1:00 p.m., there will now be two additional winners chosen at random via social media ? one winner from Facebook and one winner from Twitter!    Here?s how you can potentially win -- Look for the Facebook and Twitter posts from COGS asking you to respond by posting a selfie, comment or favorite take-away from the Extravaganza. To be eligible to win: ? You must actually attend the Extravaganza (as confirmed by checking-in upon arrival). ? You must be enrolled in at least 6 credit hours for the Spring 2018 semester. ?
